				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Any assistance will help.<a name="53466"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 23 04 4:21 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Hello,
<br />

<br />
  My first question is what kind of system are you running.  An aoe bard is only as good as their RL computer system.  I used to play EQ with an old a$ comp as a wizard.  Tried to learn Quad Kiting and could never get it.  Lag and such always got me.  You didn't elude to that possiblity of a problem so - if your system can handle AoE kites ....
<br />

<br />
  I would suggest practicing on Rockhoppers in Marus Seru.  At 51 getting hit should not be a problem, and to me Rockhoppers have been the easiest AoE target.  They seem to have a super small hit radius.  
<br />

<br />
  Secondly I would recommend not changing camera angles.  I AoE from first person, but scroll out all the way ... you know the view where you get to look at your own butt. *laughs  Anyway turn on the &quot;Target Ring&quot;.  If you run circles turning when you just start to see the target ring you should be in range.  I have found this helps me when my swarms are larger, cause if I change camera angle they always seem to catch up to me and *squish.  Anyway maybe that technique will work for you.  I know I read alot about auto-cirlce.  I can't seem to get that one down, so manual circles for me.
<br />

<br />
  You may just need to try different techniques.  Not just the camera thing but what about circle direction.  I know I can only AoE in a Clockwise direction.  Have you tried both ways?  
<br />

<br />
  Lastly - a bard isn't just AoE.  There is always charm-swarming and grouping.  Well this got kinda long...hope it may help.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
