				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Any assistance will help.<a name="55667"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 8 04 6:50 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Bards aren't about doing just one thing, as several others have said here.  If you have no luck with AE kiting, don't do it.  Simple as that.  There are so many other bardly tricks to learn (solo or group) that it just isn't worth worrying about one thing.
<br />

<br />
I learned AE kiting at 51 in Dulak, and I still kite there.  I DO autocircle, because if I didn't I would go nuts.  Manually running in circles just doesn't appeal to me.  I think now that I'm a pretty good autocircle AE kiter.
<br />

<br />
But, I can't swarm kite to save myself, and not so long ago that was THE bard solo technique everyone just HAD to know (much as you see AE kiting, now).  I can charm solo well enough, but I haven't yet felt compelled to swarm kite.  I might yet learn it, but until I do I won't consider myself much &quot;less of a bard&quot;.
<br />

<br />
Know your skills, and your limitations.  Do what you enjoy, and while by all means you should try new things, if something ain't fun, don't do it.  Being a bard is always going to be a bit of a challenge, but there are more than enough challenges to keep you occupied -- don't get hung up on just one.
<br />

<br />
The only reason you should really consider retiring your bard is if you no longer enjoy the challenge and the variety.  Even then, I'd suggest that taking a break would be better.  Play an easier class for a while.  It might make a pleasant vacation, by comparison, but you might find you miss all the action!  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
